text:
I'm so tired of stories having happy endings just for the sake of being happy. Fundamentally that is what is happening here. The villains fail because they are villains and everyone lives happily ever after. The in-between may be different but it all ends the same way. It's repetitive and boring. Here's a hint, if you have to use time-travel or some other overpowered last-minute spell/power to fix everything (Such as Trixie did in the Death of Trixie Lulamoon) then the villain probably should have won. If the hero just wins anyway what's even the point? What would have happened had the story with Care package continued before the reset? If Twilight had taken the power? Those stories could have been interesting, but they don't exist, simply because it doesn't fit the perfect happy ending. That is the problem I have with not just this, but most media. Do something interesting, don't give happy ever afters. Sometimes, just sometimes, let the villains win.

Anyway, that's my essay on storytelling, thanks for the video.
